// Sutra GUI — a Window declared in Sutra, opened in a real OS
// window by the harness in `examples/_gui_runner.py`.
//
// "GUI" here means: the Sutra source declares the window's
// structure (title, width, height) using the existing class +
// field machinery — no new runtime primitives. The harness
// compiles + executes the program, reads the returned Window
// vector's title (via the substrate-pure String accessors) and
// dimensions (via the axon-field reads that field-access already
// lowers to), and opens an actual tkinter window with those.
//
// Adding the actual rendering as a Sutra runtime intrinsic is a
// later expansion; for now the source is the declaration and the
// harness is the renderer. This is the same factoring as the
// formal-verification paper's "compile to a graph; runtime
// executes the graph" framing — here the graph is the window
// description and the runtime is tkinter.
//
// 2026-05-27.

class Window extends vector {
    field String title;
    field int width;
    field int height;
}

function Window main() {
    // Seed an empty class vector; per the field-design pattern in
    // examples/class_with_fields.su the constructor convention is
    // basis_vector("classname") + field assignments lowering to
    // axon_add under the hood.
    Window w = basis_vector("window");
    w.title = String.make_string("Sutra GUI");
    w.width = 480;
    w.height = 320;
    return w;
}
